08806nam a22009975i 9780226386935DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20071999ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226386935  a(DE-B1597)535759  a(OCoLC)1135585771  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHG3873.E18bC48 1999 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a332.456a338.4/56/09172400aChanges in Exchange Rates in Rapidly Developing Countries :bTheory, Practice, and Policy Issues /ced. by Anne O. Krueger, Takatoshi Ito. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2007] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b97 line drawings, 68 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research East Asia Seminar on Economics ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Choice of Exchange Rate Regime in Developing and Middle Income Countries -- t2 Contagious Currency Crises: Channels of Conveyance -- t3 Current Account Deficits and Capital Flows in East Asia and Latin America: Are the Early Nineties Different from the Early Eighties? -- t4 Economic Growth and Real Exchange Rate: An Overview of the Balassa-Samuelson Hypothesis in Asia -- t5 Resource Endowments and the Real Exchange Rate: A Comparison of Latin America and East Asia -- t6 Private Consumption, Nontraded Goods, and Real Exchange Rate: Evidence from South Korea and Taiwan -- t7 The Yen and Its East Asian Neighbors, 1980-1995: Cooperation or Competition? -- t8 Exchange Rate Pass-through and Industry Characteristics : The Case of Taiwan’s Exports of Midstream Petrochemical Products -- t9 Evaluation of Korea’s Exchange Rate Policy -- t10 Issues in Korean Exchange Rate Policy -- t11 Liberalization of Capital Flows in Korea: Big Bang or Gradualism? -- t12 The Foreign Exchange Allocation Policy in Postwar Japan: Its Institutional Framework and Function -- t13 The Syndrome of the Ever- Higher Yen, 1971-1995: American Mercantile Pressure on Japanese Monetary Policy -- t14 Testing for the Fundamental Determinants of the Long- Run Real Exchange Rate: The Case of Taiwan -- t15 Hong Kong’s Currency Board and Changing Monetary Regimes -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe exchange rate is a crucial variable linking a nation's domestic economy to the international market. Thus choice of an exchange rate regime is a central component in the economic policy of developing countries and a key factor affecting economic growth. Historically, most developing nations have employed strict exchange rate controls and heavy protection of domestic industry-policies now thought to be at odds with sustainable and desirable rates of economic growth. By contrast, many East Asian nations maintained exchange rate regimes designed to achieve an attractive climate for exports and an "outer-oriented" development strategy. The result has been rapid and consistent economic growth over the past few decades. Changes in Exchange Rates in Rapidly Developing Countries explores the impact of such diverse exchange control regimes in both historical and regional contexts, focusing particular attention on East Asia. This comprehensive, carefully researched volume will surely become a standard reference for scholars and policymakers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aForeign exchange -- Government policy -- Developing countries -- Congresses. 0aForeign exchange -- Government policy -- East Asia -- Congresses. 0aForeign exchange rates -- Developing countries -- Congresses. 0aForeign exchange rates -- East Asia -- Congresses. 0aForeign exchange ratesxCongressesxDeveloping countries. 0aForeign exchange ratesxCongressesxEast Asia. 0